-- BHP, Downer, Newcrest, OneSteel, Rio, Woodside: Australian Equity Preview
-- B y   S h a n i   R a j a
-- 2010-11-03T21:27:53Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-03/bhp-downer-newcrest-onesteel-rio-woodside-australian-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
whose shares may rise or fall in Australia. This preview
includes news announced after markets closed. All prices are
from yesterday’s close unless otherwise stated.  The S&P/ASX 200 Index  futures contract  due in December
gained 0.2 percent to 4,735 as of 6:59 a.m. in Sydney. The  Bank
of New York Australia ADR Index  rose 1.2 percent. The  S&P/ASX
200 Index  climbed 0.5 percent to 4,722.60.  Mining shares: The Australian government may be willing to
give a concession on its proposed minerals resource rent tax,
benefiting mining companies including BHP and Rio, the
Australian Financial Review said, citing mining sources without
identifying them.  BHP Billiton Ltd.  (BHP AU), the world’s largest mining
company, rose 0.9 percent to A$42.63 in Sydney. Its American
depositary receipts gained 1.4 percent in New York trading.  Saskatchewan is poised to sue the federal government if
Canada approves BHP Billiton Ltd.’s $40 billion hostile takeover
offer for Potash Corp. of Saskatchewan Inc., Premier Brad Wall
said.  Rio Tinto Group  (RIO AU), the world’s third-biggest miner,
added 0.8 percent to A$83.39 in Sydney.  Oil producers: Oil rose to the highest level in six months
as the Federal Reserve said it will buy an additional $600
billion of Treasuries through June to boost the economy.  Woodside Petroleum Ltd.  (WPL AU), Australia’s second-
biggest oil and gas producer, climbed 1.1 percent to A$44.08.
 Santos Ltd.  (STO AU) gained 0.6 percent to A$12.74.  Gold producers: Gold futures for December delivery dropped
as much as 2.3 percent to $1,325.50 an ounce at 2:28 p.m. in
electronic trading on the Comex in New York.  Newcrest Mining Ltd. 
(NCM AU), Australia’s largest gold producer, rose 1.2 percent to
A$40.39.  Coal of Africa Ltd.  (CZA AU): The Australian miner of the
fuel slumped the most in more than two years in Johannesburg
trading after being given until Nov. 11 to comply with South
African environmental regulations. The stock lost 0.7 percent to
A$1.39 in Sydney.       Downer EDI Ltd.  (DOW AU): The Australian engineering
company was downgraded to “underperform” from “neutral” at
Credit Suisse Group AG. Its shares dropped 2.3 percent to A$5.05.  OneSteel Ltd.  (OST AU): The second-largest Australian
producer of the alloy was raised to “outperform” from
“neutral” at Credit Suisse Group AG. The shares declined 0.4
percent to A$2.72.  To contact the reporter for this story:
 Shani Raja  in Sydney at 
 sraja4@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net . 